\maketitle
\begin{abstract}
Adversarial patches pose serious security threats to image classification
systems: physically realizable perturbations that cause persistent
misclassification across diverse inputs. We validate this threat by
generating universal patches via Projected Gradient Descent (PGD)
against AlexNet, achieving attack success rates from 4.9\% to 51.7\%,
revealing that patch vulnerability is governed by target class topology
in the model's feature space.

To counter these attacks, we present EXPA, a four-stage gradient-free
cascade defense. The core insight is that adversarial patches must
dominate model attention to cause misclassification, making them
detectable through Explainable AI (XAI) analysis. EXPA combines: a
median filter KL-divergence screen for fast suspicious-image flagging;
EigenCAM-based confirmation that identifies abnormally concentrated
activation patterns; EigenCAM heatmap localization of the patch region;
and median inpainting for patch removal and re-classification --- all
without any model retraining or backpropagation.

Evaluated across six patch/dataset combinations (ImageNette and STL-10,
three target classes), EXPA achieves 98.7\% average detection, 100\%
patch localization accuracy, and 58.4\% class restoration. EigenCAM
confirmation reduces false positives by 43.2\% over median filtering
alone (34.5\% $\rightarrow$ 19.6\%), yielding a 17.6\% average FPR
(6.9\%--19.6\% across datasets). These results demonstrate that
gradient-free XAI tools can be effectively repurposed from model
interpretation to robust adversarial defense.
\end{abstract}


\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Adversarial machine learning, explainable AI, adversarial patches, EigenCAM, image classification security, cascade defense
\end{IEEEkeywords}

\section{Introduction}

\subsection{Context}

Deep neural networks (DNNs) have achieved remarkable success in computer vision, surpassing human-level performance on numerous benchmarks. However, they exhibit a critical vulnerability: susceptibility to adversarial examples—inputs crafted to cause misclassification \cite{szegedy2013intriguing}. Among adversarial attacks, \textbf{adversarial patches} \cite{brown2017adversarial} represent a particularly dangerous class because they are physically realizable: attackers can print patches on physical media and place them in real-world environments to cause persistent misclassification.

