All six runs achieve 100\% localization accuracy and $\geq$97.9\% E2E recovery, confirming that the pipeline generalizes across different patch target classes. Class restoration varies by patch (banana: 66\%, lemon: 54--59\%, bee: 46--59\%), with bee achieving the lowest restoration on Split-1, likely due to its lower ASR (15.7\%) selecting harder edge cases.

\subsection{Impact of Localization Threshold}

The EigenCAM top-$k$ threshold controls the size of the localized patch region and directly affects recovery quality. Table~\ref{tab:topk} shows the trade-off between localization accuracy and class restoration for different threshold values.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{EigenCAM top-$k$ threshold impact (ImageNette, 28×28 patch, class 954)}
\label{tab:topk}
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
\textbf{top-$k$ threshold} & \textbf{Localization (\%)} & \textbf{Class restored (\%)} \\
\midrule
10\% & 100.0 & 54.8 \\
\textbf{5\%} & \textbf{100.0} & \textbf{66.1} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Tightening the threshold from 10\% to 5\% improves class restoration by 11.3 percentage points (54.8\% $\rightarrow$ 66.1\%) while maintaining perfect localization accuracy. This improvement occurs because tighter bounding boxes preserve more original image content around the patch, providing better context for AlexNet to make correct predictions after inpainting. The 5\% threshold represents an optimal balance for 28×28 patches on 224×224 images, maximizing class restoration while ensuring complete patch coverage.

\section{Discussion}

\subsection{Detection Performance Analysis}

The cascade architecture successfully balances sensitivity and specificity. Median filter provides high sensitivity (99.5\% TPR) by flagging any significant prediction shift under spatial smoothing, while EigenCAM reduces false alarms by verifying that prediction shifts are due to concentrated attention patterns rather than natural texture effects.

The 3.6\% missed detections (100\% − 96.4\% TPR) in the cascade correspond to patches causing subtle KL divergence shifts below the 1.0 threshold. Analysis of these cases reveals patches where PGD optimization converged suboptimally, producing weaker adversarial signals that are destroyed by median filtering but create insufficient KL divergence to trigger Stage 1 detection. This suggests that threshold tuning (lowering from 1.0 to 0.7-0.8) could improve detection sensitivity, though at the cost of increased false positives.

False positives (19.6\% on Split-1) arise from complex natural textures---brick walls, patterned fabrics, repetitive architectural elements---that exhibit two properties: (1) they shift AlexNet's predictions after median smoothing due to loss of fine-grained texture information, and (2) they create moderate spatial attention concentration. The cascade's 43.2\% relative FPR reduction compared to median filtering alone (34.5\% $\rightarrow$ 19.6\%) demonstrates that EigenCAM confirmation successfully filters many texture-induced false alarms, though further improvement remains possible.

\subsection{Localization Accuracy}

Perfect 100\% localization accuracy across all tested images demonstrates a fundamental theoretical property: adversarial patches are inherently visible to explainability tools due to their attention-dominating mechanism. This is not an empirical coincidence but rather a direct consequence of how patches achieve misclassification.

Mathematically, for a patch to cause misclassification to target class $y_t$, it must maximize the probability $P(y_t | x \oplus \delta)$. Through gradient-based optimization (PGD), the patch learns to strongly activate feature detectors associated with $y_t$ while suppressing activations for other classes. This optimization necessarily concentrates model attention—both gradients and activations—on the patch spatial region. EigenCAM's Principal Component Analysis captures this concentration as the first principal component, which explains the majority of variance in the activation maps. The patch region, by design, exhibits higher activation variance than the surrounding image, making it the dominant eigenvector direction.

This property fundamentally differs from traditional object detection, where localization requires semantic understanding of object boundaries and context. For adversarial patches, localization reduces to a simpler problem: identifying where the model's attention is most intensely concentrated. The patch reveals itself through its very mechanism of attack.

\subsection{Class Restoration and Recovery Limitations}

On ImageNette, median filter inpainting achieves 66.1\% original class restoration. The 33.9\% restoration failures fall into two categories:

\textbf{1. Semantically Critical Patch Placement (estimated 60\% of failures):} When patches cover discriminative image regions—object centers, distinctive features like faces or wheels—simple median filtering cannot reconstruct the semantic content necessary for correct classification. For example, a patch obscuring a golf ball's dimpled texture leaves a smooth white region after median inpainting; AlexNet may misclassify this as a different white spherical object. Similarly, a patch on an automobile's distinctive front grille removes identifying features, potentially causing misclassification to "truck" or other vehicle classes.

\textbf{2. Ambiguous Post-Inpainting Features (estimated 40\% of failures):} Even when patches do not cover critical regions, median filtering produces smoothed content that may lack sufficient high-frequency details for confident classification. AlexNet may recover to a semantically plausible but incorrect class. For instance, after removing a patch from a church image, the smoothed region may resemble generic building textures, causing confusion between "church," "castle," or other architectural classes.

The high target class removal rate (99.5\%) demonstrates that median filtering effectively destroys adversarial signals. However, reconstruction of the original discriminative features requires more sophisticated inpainting. This reveals a broader principle: \textit{visually realistic reconstruction does not equal classifiably correct reconstruction}. Methods like Navier-Stokes inpainting minimize perceptual distortion for human observers, but deep networks rely on specific high-frequency features that may not survive such smoothing. Median filtering, despite its coarse output, preserves local statistics that AlexNet's feature detectors rely on—which is why target class removal reaches 99.5\% while visual quality is modest. Future work could explore semantic inpainting (LaMa \cite{suvorov2022lama}, MAT) to push restoration toward 80--90\%.

\subsection{Cross-Patch and Cross-Dataset Consistency}

The results in Table~\ref{tab:allruns} reveal two important consistency findings. First, the FPR remains stable at 19.2\%--19.6\% across Split-1 (3,925 clean images) and Split-2 (9,469 clean images), confirming that the KL-divergence threshold ($\tau=1.0$) generalizes reliably to larger clean sets. Second, the 100\% localization accuracy holds universally across all three patches (banana, bee, lemon) and both splits---demonstrating that the attention-concentration property exploited by EigenCAM is a fundamental consequence of patch optimization, independent of the specific target class.

Class restoration varies by patch: banana (66\%) $>$ lemon (54--59\%) $>$ bee (46--59\%). This ordering correlates with patch ASR on Split-1: higher-ASR patches (lemon 51.7\%, bee 15.7\%) produce more difficult fooled image distributions than lower-ASR patches (banana 4.9\%). Higher ASR implies the patch successfully fools a broader range of images, including those where the original class features are less distinct from the target class---making recovery harder.

\textbf{STL-10 vs.\ ImageNette FPR Gap.} The most striking cross-dataset finding is the large FPR difference: 6.9\% on STL-10 versus 19.6\% on ImageNette (Table~\ref{tab:cascade}). Both datasets use 8,000 and 3,925 clean images respectively, ruling out sample size effects. The gap is explained by image complexity: STL-10 contains object-centric photographs of animals and vehicles at 96×96 resolution upscaled to 224×224, producing relatively smooth backgrounds that preserve model predictions under median filtering. ImageNette, by contrast, includes high-resolution images with architecturally complex scenes (churches, gas pumps, chain saws) whose intricate textures---repetitive brick patterns, mechanical grilles, foliage---shift AlexNet's predictions after median filtering even without any patch, triggering Stage~1 false alarms. This result reveals a fundamental property of the cascade: \textit{false positive rate is governed by the texture complexity of the clean set}, not by dataset size or class count. Deployments in environments with simpler backgrounds (object-centric cameras, industrial inspection) can expect FPR close to the STL-10 result (6.9\%), while natural scene datasets should anticipate higher rates similar to ImageNette (19.6\%).

\subsection{Limitations and Threats to Validity}

\textbf{1. False Positive Rate:} The 19.6\% FPR on ImageNette may be unacceptable for some deployment contexts. In autonomous vehicles or medical diagnosis where false alarms trigger expensive interventions (emergency braking, additional tests), lower FPR ($<$5\%) is necessary. Mitigation strategies include:
\begin{itemize}
\item Stricter thresholds: Increasing KL threshold from 1.0 to 1.5-2.0 trades TPR for lower FPR
\item Additional confirmation: Requiring unanimous agreement across all four EigenCAM metrics (instead of majority voting) reduces false positives
\item Temporal validation: In video contexts, requiring detection across multiple consecutive frames filters transient texture-based false alarms
\end{itemize}

\textbf{2. Non-Adaptive Attacks:} Our evaluation assumes attackers are unaware of the defense mechanism (black-box attack scenario). An adaptive attacker with knowledge of the cascade architecture could potentially craft patches that:
\begin{itemize}
\item Minimize KL divergence by optimizing patches to be robust to median filtering, ensuring $f(x \oplus \delta) \approx f(\text{MedianBlur}(x \oplus \delta))$
\item Distribute spatial attention by creating patches with spatially dispersed patterns that fool the model without concentrating activation in a small region
\item Evade multiple metrics simultaneously through multi-objective optimization
\end{itemize}

Evaluating robustness to such adaptive attacks is critical future work. Preliminary analysis suggests that the dual-constraint nature (fool the model AND evade median filtering AND avoid attention concentration) significantly increases attack difficulty, but formal analysis is needed.

\textbf{3. Limited Recovery Quality:} The 66.1\% class restoration rate, while demonstrating feasibility, indicates substantial room for improvement. Simple median filtering lacks semantic understanding of image content. Deep learning-based inpainting conditioned on surrounding context could potentially achieve 80-90\% restoration by generating semantically appropriate content rather than merely smoothing pixels.

\textbf{4. Digital-Only Evaluation:} All experiments use digitally inserted patches. Physical world deployment introduces additional challenges:
\begin{itemize}
\item Camera sensor noise and compression artifacts may obscure detection signals
\item Lighting variations alter patch appearance and effectiveness
\item Viewing angle changes affect patch visibility and position
\item Print reproduction introduces color shifts and texture variations
\end{itemize}

Physical validation on printed patches photographed under varying conditions is necessary to confirm real-world applicability.

\textbf{5. Single Architecture Evaluation:} We evaluate only on AlexNet. While AlexNet represents a widely deployed architecture, modern systems use diverse models (ResNets, EfficientNets, Vision Transformers). Defense generalization across architectures requires validation. We expect the median filter component to generalize (it operates on inputs, agnostic to architecture), but EigenCAM thresholds may require architecture-specific calibration.

\section{Conclusion}

This paper presented EXPA, a four-stage gradient-free cascade defense pipeline combining median filter detection, EigenCAM (EigenCAM-based) confirmation, heatmap-based localization, and median filter inpainting for adversarial patch mitigation. Through systematic evaluation on AlexNet across six patch/dataset combinations (Split-1 and Split-2, three target classes), we demonstrate that explainability tools originally designed for model interpretation can be effectively repurposed as robust adversarial defenses when combined with preprocessing in a cascade architecture.

The cascade reduces false positives by 43\% relative to median filtering alone (34.5\%~$\rightarrow$~19.6\%) while maintaining 96.4\% detection and 100\% localization on ImageNette, and 99.5\% TPR with only 6.9\% FPR on STL-10, yielding a 17.6\% average FPR across all runs. Tightening EigenCAM thresholding from top-10\% to top-5\% improves class restoration by 11.3 percentage points (54.8\%~$\rightarrow$~66.1\%). Attack success rates vary from 4.9\% to 51.7\% across target classes, revealing that feature-space topology governs patch vulnerability. The dual use of gradient-free median filtering and PCA-based EigenCAM enables deployment on existing models without retraining.

Future work includes integrating semantic inpainting (LaMa, MAT) to push class restoration above 80\%, evaluating adaptive attacks that jointly minimize KL divergence and attention concentration, extending the cascade to video for temporal false-positive filtering, and validating against physical printed patches across diverse architectures (ResNets, ViTs).

